# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1979-welsh-devolution-referendum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1832-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] The **1832 United Kingdom general election in Wales** was the first election held under the Reform Act 1832 and the Parliamentary Boundaries Act 1832.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1832-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] Wales saw its numbers of Members increased from 27 to 32, which includes Monmouthshire, which at the time was sometimes considered part of England.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1832-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] The Whigs, under the leadership of the Earl Grey won 18 seats (12 uncontested), against 14 (11 uncontested) for the Duke of Wellington's Tories.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1835-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] The **1835 United Kingdom general election in Wales** was held in early 1835, as the Sir Robert Peel's newly formed Conservative Party sought to strengthen its position in Parliament.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1835-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] The Whigs, under the leadership of the Viscount Melbourne, despite losing 98 seats, survived in the majority through an alliance with the Irish Radicals.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1835-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] In Wales specifically, The Whigs won 15 seats (11 uncontested), against 17 (11 uncontested) for the Conservatives, a shift of 3 seats from Whigs to Conservatives.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1837-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1837 United Kingdom general election** was held from 24 July to 18 August 1837, following the death of King William IV and the accession of Queen Victoria.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1837-united-kingdom-general-election] The election saw the Whigs secure their fourth consecutive victory, though the Conservatives, led by Robert Peel, continued to gain ground.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1837-united-kingdom-general-election] The election marked the last time that a Parliament was dissolved as a result of the demise of the Crown.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1837-united-kingdom-general-election] The dissolution of Parliament six months after a demise of the Crown, as provided for by the Succession to the Crown Act 1707, was abolished by the Reform Act 1867.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1841 United Kingdom general election** was held between 29 June and 22 July 1841.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] Following increasing government defeats, the Conservatives under Sir Robert Peel won a decisive victory against the governing Whigs.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives campaigned mainly on an 11-point programme modified from their previous electoral effort and designed by Peel, whilst the Whigs emphasised reforming the import duties on corn, replacing the existing sliding scale with a uniform rate.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whig position lost them support amongst protectionists, and the Whigs saw heavy losses in constituencies like the West Riding, where aristocratic Whig families who held a strong tradition of unbroken representation in Parliament were rejected by the electorate.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] O'Connell, who had been governing with the Whigs through a compact, felt the government's unpopularity rub off on him.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] His own party was shattered in the election.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] Barely a dozen Repealers retained their seats, and O'Connell himself lost in Dublin while his son was defeated in Carlow.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] The Chartists picked up only a few votes.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1847 United Kingdom general election** was held from 29 July to 26 August 1847.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] It saw the Conservatives win the most seats but remain divided between Protectionists and Peelites.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] This allowed the Whigs, led by Prime Minister Lord John Russell, to retain power.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election was held amid the Great Irish famine.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The Irish Repeal group won more seats than in the previous general election, while the Chartists gained the only seat they were ever to hold, Nottingham's second seat, held by Chartist leader Feargus O'Connor.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The election also witnessed the election of Britain's first Jewish MP, the Liberal Lionel de Rothschild in the City of London.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] Members being sworn in were however required to swear the Christian Oath of Allegiance, meaning Rothschild was unable actually to take his seat until the passage of the Jews Relief Act in 1858.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The constituency of Sudbury, which elected two members, was disfranchised for this election.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] This accounts there being two fewer seats in the House of Commons as compared to the previous election, though no redistribution took place.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1852 United Kingdom general election** was held from 7 to 31 July 1852.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] It produced a closely contested result between the Conservatives and Whigs, marking a significant shift in British politics, with the Conservatives increasingly representing the rural aristocracy and the Whigs the urban bourgeoisie.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] As in the previous election of 1847, Lord John Russell's Whigs won the popular vote, but the Conservative Party won a very slight majority of the seats.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] However, a split between Protectionist Tories, led by the Earl of Derby, and the Peelites who supported Lord Aberdeen made the formation of a majority government very difficult.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Lord Derby's minority, protectionist government ruled from 23 February until 17 December 1852.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Derby appointed Benjamin Disraeli as Chancellor of the Exchequer in this minority government.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] However, in December 1852, Derby's government collapsed because of issues arising out of the budget introduced by Disraeli.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] A Peelite–Whig-Radical coalition government was then formed under Lord Aberdeen.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Although the immediate issue involved in this vote of "no confidence" which caused the downfall of the Derby minority government was the budget, the real underlying issue was the repeal of the Corn Laws which Parliament had passed in June 1846 and had split the Conservative Party.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In this election, there were 18 Peelites elected in England and Wales.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The constituency of St Albans, with its two members, was disfranchised due to corruption.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] This accounts for the fact that there were two fewer seats in the House of Commons as compared to the previous election, though no redistribution took place.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] A group within the Tory/Conservative Party called the "Peelites" voted with the Whigs to achieve the repeal of the Corn Laws.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Peelites were so named because they were followers of Prime Minister Robert Peel.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In June 1846, when Peel was the Prime Minister of a Tory government, he led a group of Tory/Conservatives to vote with the minority Whigs against a majority of his own party.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] "Corn" was important to the cost of living of the average person in Britain during the early 19th century.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The term "corn" did not refer to maize, as it did in the United States.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In Britain, "corn" refers to wheat, rye and/or other grains.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Wheat, or corn, was used in the baking of bread and was the "staff of life".
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Thus the price of wheat was a very substantial part of the cost of living.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Corn Laws enforced a very high "protective" tariff against the importation of wheat into England.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] These high tariffs raised the cost of living and increased the suffering of poor people in England.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Agitation for the repeal of the Corn Laws had begun in England as early as 1837, and bills for their repeal had been introduced in Parliament each year from 1837 until their actual repeal in 1847.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] For some parliamentary leaders, like John Bright, Richard Cobden and Charles Pelham Villiers, the repeal of tariffs on imported corn was not enough.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] They wished to reduce the tariffs on all imported consumer products.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] These parliamentary leaders became known as "free traders".
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The repeal of the Corn Laws irrevocably split the Tory/Conservative party.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Peelites were not free traders, but both the Peelites and the free traders were originally Tories.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Thus both the free traders and the Peelites tended to side with the Whigs against the Tories on international trade issues.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] This presented a real threat to any government the Tories attempted to form.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The effect of this split was felt in the election of July–August 1847, when the Whig party won a 53.8% majority of seats in Parliament.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whigs knew that they could count on the Peelite Conservatives when an international trade issue came before Parliament.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In June 1852, the effects of the split in the Tory/Conservative party was having even more effect.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The period after about 1847 was one of economic stagnation in Britain.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The split in the Tory party was a significant cause of the reformation of the political parties in Britain in the February 1852 election.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] As noted above, in the election of 1852 the protectionist rump of the Conservatives became the party of the rural landholders, while the Liberals and Peelites became the party of the towns, boroughs and growing urban industrial areas of Britain.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1852, England elected 244 Conservatives and 216 non-Conservatives; Wales elected 20 Conservatives and 12 non-Conservatives, Scotland elected 20 Conservatives and 33 non-Conservatives, Ireland elected 40 Conservatives and 63 non-Conservatives whereas the Universities elected 6 Conservatives.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The election of 1852 returned a majority in support of free-trade, but the minority Conservative government continued in office.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] An opportunity for the opposition arose in December 1852, when the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Benjamin Disraeli, introduced the budget of the Derby minority government.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Due to the worsening economic situation, the budget imposed a number of tax increases on the profits of the middle class and granted some tax cuts for the rural landed aristocracy.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The budget also extended the income tax to the Irish middle class, angering some of the members from Ireland who had supported the minority government on the Irish Church issue and were opposed to the previous Prime Minister, the Liberal leader Lord John Russell.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Consequently, a number of Irish Conservatives voted against the minority government on the Disraeli budget on 17 December 1852.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] This vote of "no confidence" caused the government to fall.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the fall of the minority government, Lord Aberdeen was called on to form a government, since the Irish Conservatives who opposed Disraeli's budget were opposed to Lord John Russell on religious issues and he formed a Peelite/Whig coalition government on 19 December 1852.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] This government served until 30 January 1855, when it too collapsed due to issues surrounding British involvement in the Crimean War.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] While the Conservatives had, in theory, a slim majority over the Whigs, the party was divided between Protectionist and Peelite wings: the former numbered about 290 and the latter 35–40.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whigs themselves represented a coalition of old Whigs (conservative Protestant/dissenter aristocrats), Liberals, Radicals, and Irish nationalists.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The above numbers therefore do not represent the true balance of support in Parliament.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1859 United Kingdom general election** was held from 28 April to 18 May 1859 following the defeat of Prime Minister the Earl of Derby's Conservative government in a vote of confidence.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] The newly formed Liberal Party, led by Viscount Palmerston, secured victory despite winning fewer seats than in the previous election.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] There is no separate tally of votes or seats for the Peelites.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] They did not contest elections as an organised party but more as independent Free trade Conservatives with varying degrees of distance from the two main parties.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] It was also the last general election entered by the Chartists, before their organisation was dissolved.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] As of 2024, this is the last election in which the Conservatives won the most seats in Wales.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was the quietest and least competitive between 1832 and 1885, with most county elections being uncontested.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] The election also saw the lowest number of candidates between 1832 and 1885, with Tory gains potentially being the result of a lack of opposition as much as a change in public opinion.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] the government which Palmerston organized in June 1859 was a coalition of a different kind: not a coalition of groups which looked back to the past, but a coalition which anticipated the future.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] Had it not been for Palmerston himself—too individual, too full of personality to be fitted into a party-pattern—it would have been the first Liberal government in our history.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] Everything that was important in it was Liberal—finance, administrative reform, its very composition: the first government with unmistakable middle-class Free Traders as members.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The **1979 Welsh devolution referendum** was a post-legislative referendum held on 1 March 1979 (Saint David's Day) to decide whether there was sufficient support for a Welsh Assembly among the Welsh electorate.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The referendum was held under the terms of the Wales Act 1978 drawn up to implement proposals made by the Kilbrandon Report published in 1973.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The plans were defeated by a majority of 4:1 (20.3% for and 79.7% against) with only 12% of the Welsh electorate voting in favour of establishing an assembly.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] A second referendum to create a devolved assembly for Wales was held in 1997, which led to the enactment of the Government of Wales Act 1998 and the creation of the National Assembly for Wales in 1999.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Both the Scotland Act and the Wales Act contained a requirement that at least 40% of all voters back the plan.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] It had been passed as an amendment by Islington South MP George Cunningham with the backing of Bedwellty MP Neil Kinnock.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Kinnock, the future leader of the Labour Party, called himself a "unionist".
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] His stated view was that "between the mid-sixteenth century and the mid-eighteenth century Wales had practically no history at all, and even before that it was the history of rural brigands who have been ennobled by being called princes".
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] He was one of six south Wales Labour MPs who opposed their own Government's plans, along with Leo Abse (Pontypool), Donald Anderson (Swansea East), Ioan Evans (Aberdare), Fred Evans (Caerphilly), and Ifor Davies (Gower).
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The government of James Callaghan did not have an overall majority in the House of Commons, and was therefore vulnerable to opposition from within its own ranks.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Labour party was split on home rule for Wales with a vocal minority opposed.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] They considered devolution as a danger to the unity of the UK and a concession to Welsh nationalism in the wake of by-election victories by Plaid Cymru.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Labour Party committed itself to devolution after coming to power in the February 1974 General Election.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] It followed the findings of a Royal Commission on the Constitution under Lord Kilbrandon.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Set up in 1969 in the wake of pressure to address growing support for independence in Scotland and Wales it delivered a split report in 1973.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Royal Commission recommended legislative and executive devolution to Scotland and Wales, with a minority supporting advisory Regional Councils for England.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] This plan was rejected as too bureaucratic and ill-advised in economic terms.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] New plans were brought forward by Harold Wilson's government in 1975 and 1976 which confined devolution to Scotland and Wales.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Scotland and Wales Bill had a difficult passage through Parliament and the government, lacking a majority to pass the plan, withdrew the legislation and introduced separate Bills for Scotland and Wales.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Hostile Labour MPs from the north of England, Wales and Scotland combined to insist that Assemblies could only be passed if directly endorsed by voters in a post-legislative referendum.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] In 1978, John Morris, Baron Morris of Aberavon was under the impression that James Callaghan would call a general election in the autumn, but called it off.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] On 1 March, Saint David's Day, the devolution referendum was held but came at the end of the Winter of Discontent.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Factors such as "tribalism" divisions within Wales and impressions that a Welsh Assembly would be dominated by people of one particular region could have potentially caused the proposal to be rejected.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] According to John Morris, people in southern Wales were persuaded by the No campaign that the Assembly would be dominated by "bigoted Welsh-speakers from the north and the west" whilst in northern Wales, people had been convinced the Assembly would be a dominated Glamorgan County Council "Taffia".
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] These factors led to a failed devolution referendum.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Proposals for a more powerful Assembly in Scotland attracted the support of a majority of those who voted (1,230,937 for, 1,153,502 against) (see 1979 Scottish devolution referendum), but it amounted to just 32.5% of the total electorate, lower than the 40% threshold required.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] The results sealed the fate of the minority Labour government, and as a direct result of the defeat of the referendums in Wales and Scotland the Scottish National Party (SNP) withdrew its support for the government, though Plaid Cymru supported the government in exchange for political concessions.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] In the House of Commons on 28 March 1979, the Labour government was defeated on a motion of no confidence by one vote, only the second time in the 20th century that a government was brought down in this way.
[src:1979-welsh-devolution-referendum/1979-welsh-devolution-referendum] Labour's defeat in the 1979 General Election to Margaret Thatcher's Conservative Party precipitated a civil war within its own ranks, and the party was to be out of office for eighteen years.
